Pneumococcal (pneumococcal) (pneumococcal) vaccine: one injection, You should receive it as soon as you have been diagnosed with HIV.

Monosaccharide (pneumonia) vaccine: One injection every five years. You should receive it shortly after being diagnosed with HIV, but you should wait if your CD4 cell count is less than 200. Polysaccharide vaccine: You should get one to two injections of it after being diagnosed. You have HIV.

Tetanus and pertussis vaccine: one injection every 10 years. Hepatitis A virus (HAV): You need to have two injections for 6 months. If your CD4 cell count is less than 200, you must wait to receive this vaccine until the cell count exceeds 200.

Hepatitis A / Hepatitis B virus: You need to get 3 injections over 6 months. This is available for people who need HAV and HBV vaccines. Human papillomavirus (HPV): You need to have 3 injections over a period of 6 months. Meningococcal: Bacterial meningitis vaccine, two injections over two months.
